\section{Settlements}

\key{Map}: When you
\href{https://alexschroeder.ch/wiki/2011-01-13_Campaign_Start}{create
  a new campaign}, start with
\href{https://alexschroeder.ch/wiki/2009-12-02_Hexcrawl}{a small hex
  map}.\marginnote{Maps are inspiring. They provide a sense of place,
  and every landmark they contain is a potential exploration goal, yet
  another option for players to pursue. Keep a campaign map, hand out
  treasure maps, let other characters draw maps for the party. Players
  need options, and maps are like option tokens. Maps are also props
  that are very easy to make.} You could use the
\href{https://campaignwiki.org/text-mapper}{random hexmap generator},
for example. Only worry about ruins and lairs in the various hexes
once players actually explore the region. This creates an
\href{https://alexschroeder.ch/wiki/2007-02-14_DM_Advice_–_Organic_Campaigns}{organic
  campaign}. Start with the wilderness surrounding a small settlement.

\key{Settlements}: Every settlement has two or three interesting,
named people. These are the people of authority, who the players are
likely to talk to. Every settlement should have a building or two
where these named people can be found, and an inn, or an explanation
for the lack of an inn. Don't bother with a map for the settlement.

\key{People}: Most of civilization consists of neutral, egoistical,
normal humans and appropriate demihumans from the monster manual.
Don't bother assigning levels unless these people are
important.\marginnote{Treat high level humans like monsters with
  special powers: these are the special powers they acquired during
  their many adventures. If you painstakingly create high level
  spell casters with all their spells, your lengthy notes will confuse
  you at the table.}

