  \includegraphics{Basilisk.jpg}
\end{marginfigure}

The basilisk is the ``little king of serpents''---it's a monstrous
snake ten paces long and nearly chest high at its thickest. The
basilisk's scales are usually green or brown, and upon its head it
wears a crown of gold. Its lair is filled with toxic fumes, a deadly
poison to all. Its breath poisons the air for \SI{30}{ft} around it.
\textbf{When you breathe in these fumes}, save vs.~poison or die. You
can hold your breath for one round and fight. If you keep fighting,
save vs.~death or faint. Once you faint, your body starts
breathing again, at which point you must save vs.~poison or die.
Its gaze also kills; such is the power of its poisonous spirit.
\textbf{If it sees you}, and you did not have to save vs.~poison this
round, do so now or die. And finally, if you manage to approach the
basilisk without being slain by its stench or gaze, you still have to
survive it poisonous fangs. \textbf{If you are hit}, and you did not
have to save vs.~poison this round, do so now or die.

\begin{quote}
  HD~6+1 AC~16 1d10 + \emph{poison} F6 MV~6 ML~9 XP~600
\end{quote}

\textbf{Numbers}: 1. The basilisk lives alone. The general area where
a basilisk rules might feature a lot of snakes, but none approach
a basilisk's lair and none fight intruders. The basilisk hatches
from a cursed egg lain by a cock and is thus also known as a
cockatrice. It never mates.

\textbf{Ingredients}: If you're a trained assassin,\marginnote{To be
  trained as an assassin, you must swear eternal loyalty and servitude
  to \hyperref[sec:set]{Set}.} you can fill 10 vials with a bright
green poison so strong that breaking the vial requires anybody
within \SI{10}{ft} to save vs.~poison or die.

\terror These are the belongings of all the dead villagers and
soldiers foolish enough to approach. In addition to the treasure
listed above, a golden diadem worth \SI{500}{gp}.

