\begin{marginfigure}
  \includegraphics{Lycanthrope.jpg}
\end{marginfigure}

Lycanthropy is a powerful disease. It turns ordinary humans into
werewolves---and the full moon turns them into bloodthirsty
beasts.\marginnote{Lycanthrope and werewolf both translate to
  man-wolf, according to
  \href{https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Werewolf}{Wikipedia}: Old
  English: wer, ``man'', and Greek: lykos, ``wolf'', anthropos, ``human''.}
Their body changes into a bestial half human, half wolf, with long
claws, a terrible jaw, and it fills their minds with lust for blood.
The victims do not remember their acts of murder and try to hide
evidence of their rampage: torn clothes, dead bodies, broken doors
and an unbelievable amount of blood. After a few months, the victims
that managed to remain hidden and avoided a lynching learn to accept
their true nature and leave human societies to live amongst their new
kin. They forget about their human lives and shapes, eventually.

In their bestial shape, they can \textbf{only be harmed by magic or
  silver weapons}. Their howls will \textbf{call wolves} from nearby
forests. These wolves arrive within ten minutes. They cannot stand the
touch of \textbf{wolfbane}---a toxic flower that can be bought from
old people at markets but which wilts within a few days. Seeing it
forces a morale check and getting hit by it forces them to flee.

\begin{quote}
HD~4 AC~15 1d10 F4 MV~18 ML~8 XP~400; requires magic or silver to hit;
call wolves
\end{quote}

Any human \textbf{killed by a werewolf} does not actually
die.\marginnote{This applies only to humans! This is also why
  villagers are suspicious of anybody spending a few days in the
  forest. Who knows, maybe they caught the disease? They will be
  watched anxiously for scars and torn clothes.} Instead, they
recover within a day or two, and on the next night of the full moon,
they'll turn into a werewolf.

\textbf{Numbers}: 2d6, but there will always be another 2d6
\hyperref[sec:wolf]{wolves} in the vicinity.

\textbf{Names}: Konrad, Lilly, Marcus, Nora, Oliver, Pentesilea,
Quinton.

\poor Monthly bloodlust and insanity does not result in much treasure.

\textbf{Terrain}: forests, ruins.

Many similar diseases exists: \textbf{wererats} rule the sewers of big
cities, \textbf{werebears} keep dark forests safe, \textbf{wereboars}
take over remote mills, \textbf{werecats} terrorize remote villages,
and so on. Use the same stats for all of them, but instead of calling
wolves, these call their appropriate kin instead.



\section{Manticore}
