Medusas are creatures cursed by a desperate need for love and yet
their looks cause bitter death: anybody seeing the living snakes in
their hair must save vs.~petrification or \textbf{turn to stone}.
Blind fighting or using a mirror to fight incurs the usual penalty of
-4 to hit.

Approaching a medusa also allows the snakes on her head to attack.
Their bite is \textbf{poisonous} and leads to death in \SI{10}{min}.

Note that there is no known way to turn petrified creatures back to
flesh.\marginnote{That's because this game is limited to spells up to
  the 5\th circle. Everything else is divine
  intervention.} And worse: since petrified victims are not really
dead, their soul remain imprisoned in their stone bodies for all
eternity. Some scholars speculate that grinding these statues to dust
and washing them away into the sea, or letting the acid and rain erode
it away to nothingness is the only way to free those imprisoned souls.

\begin{quote}
  HD~4 AC~12 1d6 or \emph{poison} F6 MV~9 ML~8 XP~400;
  \emph{petrification}
\end{quote}

\textbf{Numbers}: 1. Sometimes \hyperref[sec:scorpion]{giant
  scorpions} can be found nearby.

\textbf{Names}: Agace, Iolente, Mireille, Shambleau, Tisbe, Ysmaine.

\terror These are the treasures of the men and women she charmed and
killed.

\textbf{Terrain}: deserts, ruins.



\section{Minotaur}
\label{sec:minotaur}
\index{Minotaur}
\caves{Minotaur}
\mountains{Minotaur}
\begin{marginfigure}
  \includegraphics{Minotaur.jpg}
\end{marginfigure}

Minotaurs are cow people. They are broad and strong, with great horns
and beautiful eyes. If they remain in an area for a few days, a
\emph{mental maze} slowly starts to form around them. Once they
stay for many weeks, a \emph{hedge maze} will start to grow. And
finally, after a few years, a \emph{stone maze} starts to grow.
This is a permanent effect and the only way to avoid it is to always
keep on the move.

\begin{quote}
HD~6 AC~14 2d6 F6 MV~12 ML~11 XP~600
\end{quote}

\textbf{Spells}: The creation of mazes being a special ability of
minotaurs they cannot be taught. But they might be studied in order to
research such spells.

\emph{Mental Maze} (3\rd circle) acts as a confusing area effect
extending \SI{300}{ft} in all directions. Anybody entering the area
must save vs.~spells or soon leave it again, not having found what
they were looking for.

\emph{Hedge Maze} (4\th circle) grows plants until they create a
physical maze extending \SI{300}{ft} in all directions after
\SI{1}{h}. The hedge remains and cannot be dispelled. If the magic is
dispelled, the hedge slowly withers and dies over the coming week. The
thorny walls are \SI{20}{ft} high and difficult to burn and hard to
cross. It's much easier to search the maze, given that there is always
a way to reach its centre.

\emph{Stone Maze} (5\th circle) raises a stone maze from the ground
extending \SI{300}{ft} in all directions after \SI{10}{min}. These
stones will remain and cannot be dispelled. The stone walls are
\SI{30}{ft} high.

\textbf{Numbers}: 1d8.

\textbf{Names}: Silence, Calm, Patience, Rage, Axe, Gore.

\poor This is the plunder of their roving years, if any.

\textbf{Terrain}: caves, mountains.



\section{Mummy}
\label{sec:mummy}
\index{Mummy}
\caves{Mummy}

Mummies are ancient sorcerer kings which their descendants saw fit to
preserve for their knowledge and wisdom. But after a hundred years or
more their dynasty has failed, their descendants are dead, but they
are still around, their opinion not wanted, their advice not heeded,
their tombs no longer guarded. Some of them might still welcome
visitors from the dark recesses of their burial chambers, offering
ancient advice and knowledge, but most are simply filled with cold
hate, robbed of their spell casting powers of old, fallen from grace,
preserved for an eternal afterlife that never came.

Anybody who sees them must save vs.~paralysis or be \textbf{held}.
This hold disappears if the victim can no longer see the mummy or if
the mummy attacks anybody.\marginnote{Blind fighting incurs a -4
  penalty.} Mummies holding their victims will leave the killing to
the rest of their family or other undead minions unaffected by their
power.

\begin{quote}
  HD~5+1 AC~14 1d12 F6 MV~6 ML~12 XP~500; \emph{hold}; only harmed by
  magic or magic weapons; always fail their save vs.~spells against
  fire spells; unaffected by \emph{sleep}, \emph{charm}, and other
  such mind affecting spells
\end{quote}

\begin{marginfigure}
  \includegraphics{Mummy.jpg}
\end{marginfigure}

\textbf{Spells}: The only power that they managed to hold on to was to
bedazzle and terrorize the living.

\emph{Hold} (4\th circle) forces anybody seeing you within \SI{60}{ft}
to save vs.~paralysis or be unable to move, experiencing a cold hand
squeezing their heart and the shrivelling of their eyes, their tongue,
their intestines. A held person will not drop anything and remain
standing, staring at you in utter fear. Attacking anybody or leaving
the victims' field of vision ends the hold.

\textbf{Numbers}: 1d8. A tomb usually holds multiple mummies of a
ruling dynasty. Often found in the company of
\hyperref[sec:zombie]{zombies}.

\textbf{Names}: Beauty of the Stars, Light of Heaven, Sky Lord, Horse
Lord, Chariot Empress, Lord of the River.

\dead These are the riches they were buried with -- unless their tomb
has already been plundered.

\textbf{Terrain}: caves.



