\section{Rakshasa}
\label{sec:rakshasa}
\index{Rakshasa}
\begin{marginfigure}
  \includegraphics{Rakshasa.jpg}
\end{marginfigure}

Rakshasa are tiger demons in humanoid form. They are all natural
planar travelers, always looking for magic items, beautiful people and
strange beasts. They like to surround themselves in their demiplane
palaces with traps and treasures, dangerous animals and human slaves,
unwilling to associate with their own kind, hungry for power and
security, fearing betrayal and murder.

The rakshasa are tricksters, shape changers and master of illusion. It
is said that the older ones no longer remember their original shape.
The only way it shall be revealed is when they die.

\begin{quote}
  HD~9 AC~18 1d4/1d4/1d6 E7 MV~12 ML~8 XP~900; spells: \emph{illusion},
  \emph{invisibility}, \emph{shape change}, \emph{conflagration} for
  9d6 damage up to \SI{180}{ft}, \emph{domination}, \emph{dimension
    door}, \emph{plane shift}\marginnote{Rakshasa are like magic
    users, limited by spells/day. Thus: 2\nd~and 3\rd~circle, 3×/day;
    4\th~circle, 2×/day; 5\th~circle, 1×/day.}
\end{quote}

\textbf{Spells}: Rakshasa can teach you spells in exchange for
services rendered.

\emph{Illusion} (2\nd~circle) allows you to create and maintain an
illusion as large as a house for as long as you concentrate on it.
Anybody touching it may save vs.~spells in order to see through the
illusion. An illusion attacks like the caster but always has AC~10.
Illusionary damage will affect you as long as you believe it until you
faint.

\emph{Invisibility} (2\nd circle) makes you invisible until you attack
somebody.

\emph{Conflagration} (3\rd~circle) weakens the boundaries to the
planes of eternal fire anywhere within \SI{180}{ft} and causes the
floors and walls in a circle with a diameter of \SI{40}{ft} to erupt
in flames dealing 1d6 damage per level and destroying any flammable
material.

\emph{Shape change} (3\rd circle) allows you to change your body, as
long as your shape remains roughly human. The number of your limbs and
your mass remain unchanged. Copying the look of a specific person
takes about \SI{10}{min}. You return to your original shape when
slain.

\emph{Domination} (4\th~circle) turns \emph{any} on creature into a
loyal friend, or up to 3d6 creatures with \SI{3}{HD} or less. Note
that the undead are still immune to this charm. The target is granted
a saving throw vs.~spells.\marginnote[-5em]{As time passes, more
  saving throws are granted to the target:
  
  \medskip
  \begin{tabular}{cl}
    Intelligence & Timeframe \\
    3–8 & monthly \\
    9–12 & weekly \\
    13–18 & daily \\
  \end{tabular}}

\emph{Dimension Door} (4\th~circle) allows you to send yourself or
another up to \SI{360}{ft} away in any direction.\marginnote{Unwilling
  targets get no saving throw.} You do not need to see or know the
target area. If the target area is occupied, the spell fails without
any adverse effects.

\emph{Plane Shift} (5\nd circle) allows you to transport yourself and
up to four other creatures of comparable size or less to any place in
the multiverse. You need to know the place, so most of the time you
will need to find books describing target locations in great
detail.\marginnote{Just having been in an area does not grant you the
  detailed arcane knowledge required. You will need to keep a list of
  target areas you know.}

\textbf{Numbers}: 1. When met out in the world, searching for lost
treasure, in the company of 2d6 human slaves; when met in their
palace, in the company of 1d4×10 human slaves.

\begin{quote}
HD~1 HP 1d4 AC~13 1d6 T1 MV~12 ML~7 XP~100; double damage on a surprise
attack.
\end{quote}

\textbf{Names}: Argus the Watchful, Zeno the Wise, Cassandra the Seer,
Priam the Rich, Helen the Beautiful.

\rich Collection of trinkets and treasures found on their travels.

\textbf{Terrain}: none.



\section{Salamander}
\label{sec:salamander}
\index{Salamander}
\fire{Salamander}
\begin{marginfigure}
  \includegraphics{Salamander.jpg}
\end{marginfigure}

Salamanders are elemental creatures of fire, half man, half worm, up
to \SI{16}{ft} long. They are not subjects of the
\hyperref[sec:ifrit]{afarit} and no friends of the
\hyperref[sec:giant]{fire giants}. They don't build cities, preferring
to live by themselves in the lava lakes of
\hyperref[key:Muspelheim]{Muspelheim}.

They radiate such \textbf{intense heat} that anybody within
\SI{20}{ft} takes 1d8 damage \emph{every round}.

\begin{quote}
HD~8 AC~18 1d4/1d4/1d8 F8 MV~12 ML~8 XP~800; \emph{heat}, immune to
fire; only harmed by magic or magic weapons; unaffected by
\emph{sleep}, \emph{charm}, and other such mind affecting
spells\marginnote{Salamanders are simple creatures, old but not
  wise. Many sorcerers have tried to study them and learn the secrets
  of \emph{fire resistance} or \emph{heat production}, but they have
  all failed.}
\end{quote}

\textbf{Numbers}: 2d4.

\textbf{Names}: Hot, Melt, Flow, Lake, Pit, Pain, Ash.

\textbf{Ingredients}: Bathing in the fresh blood of a salamander 
makes you immune to fire for as long as you remain close to an open
fire.\marginnote{A torch, a campfire, even a lowly candle will do. But
  if the fire ever goes out, the immunity fades within
  \SI{10}{min}.}

\terror On cooler islands in their lava lakes they store the valuables
they took from the fools that disturbed their peace.

\textbf{Terrain}: fire.



\section{Scorpion, Giant}
\label{sec:scorpion}
\index{Scorpion}
\deserts{Scorpion}
\caves{Scorpion}
\begin{marginfigure}
  \includegraphics{Scorpion.jpg}
\end{marginfigure}

Giant scorpions are the result of small scorpions coming into contact
with Earth Blood, often due to malevolent sorcerers breeding steeds
for their most powerful servants. They are as big as coaches and their
pincers can cut a grown man in twain. Anybody stung by their
\textbf{barbed tail} must save vs.~poison or die.

\begin{quote}
HD~4 AC~18 1d10/1d10/1d4 + \emph{poison} F2 MV~15 ML~11 XP~400
\end{quote}

\textbf{Numbers}: 1d6, but often with \hyperref[sec:warlock]{warlocks}
using them as \textbf{mounts}, or with a \hyperref[sec:medusa]{medusa}
nearby.

\textbf{Ingredients}: Sadly, the poison of a scorpion must be injected
and unless you have a huge syringe lying around, this is difficult.
Some desperate souls have tied scorpion tails to a short piece of rope
and used it as a poisonous throwing hammer. It's worth a shot. If you
hit, the target must save vs.~poison or die---and the scorpion tail
loses it's poison.

\notreasure

\textbf{Terrain}: caves, deserts.


\section{Sea Serpent}
\label{sec:serpent}
\index{Sea Serpent}
\water{Sea Serpent}
\begin{marginfigure}
  \includegraphics{Sea-Serpent.jpg}
\end{marginfigure}

Sea serpents live in lakes and oceans and love to destroy ships and
eat sailors. Each attack targeting a person also damages the ship.

\begin{quote}
HD~6 AC~15 2d6 and 1d10 vs.~ships F3 MV~15 ML~8 XP~600
\end{quote}

\textbf{Numbers}: 2d6.

\textbf{Ingredients}: The glistening scales of sea serpents have been
used by coastal elves to build their silent, silver armor. It grants
AC~15, allows the wearer to swim and to move silently, but it must be
kept in a box full of sea water every night.

\notreasure If there's any treasure at all, it is at the bottom of the
sea. If so, roll for some \hyperref[sec:human]{human} treasure.

\textbf{Terrain}: water.



\section{Shadow}
\label{sec:shadow}
\index{Shadow}
\caves{Shadow}
\begin{marginfigure}
  \includegraphics{Shadow.jpg}
\end{marginfigure}

Shadows are two-dimensional creatures entering the middle realm where
humans live through cracks in reality where light and darkness meet.
Suddenly extra shadows are dancing on cave walls, \textbf{surprising}
their foes on 1–5 in 6. When they touch your shadow, they
\textbf{drain} your strength. Anybody who is reduced to zero strength
must die and rise as a shadow within a few hours. To destroy them, use
spells or the \emph{shadows} of magic weapons.

\begin{quote}
HD~2 AC~13 1d4 + 1 strength F2 MV~15 ML~8 XP~200; only harmed by magic
or magic weapons; unaffected by \emph{sleep}, \emph{charm}, and other
such mind affecting spells; surprise
\end{quote}

\textbf{Numbers}: 1d8.

\terror This is what you find on the shriveled corpses of their
victims in the vicinity.

\textbf{Terrain}: caves.



\section{Shark}
\label{sec:shark}
\index{Shark}
\water{Shark}
\begin{marginfigure}
  \includegraphics{Shark.jpg}
\end{marginfigure}

Sharks are efficient and quiet hunters of the sea. Much like
\hyperref[sec:fish]{giant fish} they are sometimes used by underwater
civilizations to guard their realms, magic users \emph{polymorph} into
shark form, and some people have shark pools, of course.

\begin{quote}
HD~4 AC~16 2d6 F2 MV~18 ML~7 XP~400
\end{quote}

The largest sharks are true terrors of the sea. And who knows what
sharks the inky depths are hiding?

\begin{quote}
HD~8 AC~16 2d10 F4 MV~18 ML~7 XP~800
\end{quote}

\textbf{Numbers}: 2d6 sharks or 1d4 giant sharks.

\notreasure If the sharks are found near a sunken ship,
you can roll for some \hyperref[sec:human]{human} treasure.

\textbf{Terrain}: water.



\section{Skeleton}
\label{sec:skeleton}
\index{Skeleton}
\caves{Skeleton}
\undead{Skeleton}
\begin{marginfigure}
  \includegraphics{Skeleton.jpg}
\end{marginfigure}

Skeletons are the simplest undead guardians to raise for a
necromancer. Once raised, the skeletons remain forever unless
slain, guarding whatever they were ordered to guard, unwavering, loyal
to the end. Too bad they're so slow. They can't be rushed. In addition
to that, their \emph{morale} is bad. When skeletons fail their morale
check, the necromantic control propelling them forward breaks down.
They lose cohesion, slow down, stop attacking or fall apart, taking a
few minutes to resume their task.

\begin{quote}
HD~1 AC~13 1d6 F1 MV~6 ML~7 XP~100; unaffected by \emph{sleep},
\emph{charm}, and other such mind affecting spells
\end{quote}

\textbf{Spells}: Over millennia, human bones\marginnote{Why are these
  skeletons always human skeletons? Nobody knows.} have been
accumulating in the soft ground beneath our feet. If you're standing
on ground that can be dig up, you can raise skeletons.

\emph{Raise skeletons} (3\rd~circle) summons a skeleton per level from
the ground beneath your feet. They dig themselves up in
\SI{10}{min}. It is up to you to arm them. Skeletons can wield any
weapon and wear any armor. Skeletons will guard the place or person
you indicate for all eternity, until they or their charge are
destroyed at which time they will crumble and fall apart.

\textbf{Numbers}: A typical tomb is guarded by 3d10 skeletons.

\notreasure Most skeletons guard entrances to tombs and the like.
There must be treasure around here somewhere, but the skeletons
themselves have none.

\textbf{Terrain}: caves.



\section{Snake, Giant}
\label{sec:snake}
\index{Snake}
\caves{Snake}
\jungles{Snake}
\begin{marginfigure}
  \includegraphics{Snake.jpg}
\end{marginfigure}

Snake pits are a favorite trap of assassin guilds and
\hyperref[sec:set]{Set} temples. These snakes are as long as a human
is tall and their bite is \textbf{poisonous}. Anybody bitten must save
vs.~poison or die. One of the first \emph{boons} granted by Set is the
ability to walk among snakes without being attacked.

\begin{quote}
HD~2 AC~14 1d4 + \emph{poison} F1 MV~9 ML~7 XP~200
\end{quote}

Giant snakes are often used as guardians of the inner sanctum of
temples. These are the favorite pets of high priests. They don't bite
but once they hit with their tail, they \textbf{constrict} you,
making you \emph{helpless}: unable to move, unable to attack. The next
round, you are reduced to \SI{0}{HP} and must roll on the
\emph{Injury and Death} table every round while you and the snake are
alive.

\begin{quote}
HD~5 AC~14 2d6 + \emph{constrict} F3 MV~9 ML~8 XP~500
\end{quote}

\textbf{Numbers}: A snake pit will be filled with 1d8 snakes; an inner
sanctum will have but 1 giant snake.

\notreasure If the snakes are guarding a temple, you can
roll for some \hyperref[sec:human]{human} treasure.

\textbf{Terrain}: caves, jungles.



\section{Spectre}
\label{sec:spectre}
\index{Spectre}
\caves{Spectre}
\undead{Spectre}
\begin{marginfigure}
  \includegraphics{Spectre.jpg}
\end{marginfigure}

Spectres are powerful witch kings and queens, undead servants of
ancient evil powers seduced by rings of power and the like. They are
formless spirits wearing cloaks, crowns and swords in order to have an
effect in the world.

That is why they fear running water: it washes these items away and
reduce them to powerless voices. Finding replacements usually takes
many days. Without their gear, spectres can fly with MV~30.

When stabbed by a spectre, victims are immediately \textbf{drained of
  two levels}.\marginnote{Victims reroll their remaining hit dice and
  keep this new hit point maximum if it is lower than their previous
  maximum. If their current hit points are higher than the new
  maximum, reduce them as well. Victims also lose their two best
  spells, if any, and reduce saving throws as appropriate.} Reduced to
zero levels, the victim rises as a spectre come midnight and join
the cause of their killer.

\begin{quote}
HD~6 AC~18 1d8 + \emph{drain} F6 MV~15 ML~11 XP~600; only harmed by
magic or magic weapons; unaffected by \emph{sleep}, \emph{charm}, and
other such mind affecting spells
\end{quote}

\textbf{Numbers}: 1d4.

\ancient This is what they are wearing and the treasure they are
guarding.

\textbf{Terrain}: caves.



\section{Spider, Giant}
\label{sec:spider}
\index{Spider}
\forests{Spider}
\caves{Spider}
%% \begin{marginfigure}
%%   \includegraphics{Spider.jpg}
%% \end{marginfigure}

These are big spiders.\marginnote{Spiders don't have a ``web'' attack
  where they throw sticky fibres are their opponents. Their webs are
  \emph{traps}. If you run into them because you had no light or you
  were fleeing in a panic, you're stuck. Struggling just entangles you
  more. It's like quicksand. You need friends to rescue you.} They
like to climb. They are fast. They like to get the drop on you. They
like to keeps their victims paralysed: alive and fresh.

\begin{quote}
HD~4 AC~14 1d6 + \emph{paralysis} F2 MV~15 ML~7 XP~400; climb
\end{quote}

\textbf{Numbers}: 1d4.

\poor The former possessions of their victims might be found buried
under a pile of bones.

\textbf{Terrain}: caves, forests.



\section{Squid, Giant}
\label{sec:squid}
\index{Squid}
\index{Octopus, see {Squid}}
\index{Kraken, see {Squid}}
\water{Squid, Giant}
\begin{marginfigure}
  \includegraphics{Squid.jpg}
\end{marginfigure}

Squids have eight arms and two tentacles, octopuses have eight
arms.\marginnote{Giant squid can attack and damage a ship directly
  instead of fighting sailors, but consider what this leads to: player
  characters have nowhere to run, have nobody to parlay with, and if
  they lose the fight, they all drown in their armor. You need to
  think of ways to make this part of a good adventure.} The inside
surfaces of these are lined with suction cups whose circumference is
again lined with serrated chitin. In addition to that, they have a
beak to chew their victims and a tongue with small, file-like teeth to
shred their victims. When arms or tentacles hit, they
\textbf{attach} themselves to their victim. From now on, they'll deal
automatic damage until the victim is dead. The beak bites one of
the victims the squid is already attached to.

\begin{quote}
HD~6 AC~13 8–10×1d6/1d10 F3 MV~12 ML~7 XP~600; attach
\end{quote}

There are also huge, ship-sized kraken, monsters summoned from the
abyss. These will readily attack harbors. When their tentacles hit,
the victims are simply \textbf{flung} through the air, either crashing
into something solid for an additional 3d6 damage, or falling into the
water to drown: you cannot swim in metal armor.

\begin{quote}
HD~12 AC~16 8×2d6 F6 MV~9 ML~10 XP~1200; fling
\end{quote}

\textbf{Numbers}: 1.

\notreasure If the giant squid is found in a sunken ship,
you can roll for some \hyperref[sec:human]{human} treasure.

\textbf{Terrain}: water.


\section{Swamp Crane}
\label{sec:crane}
\index{Crane, Swamp}
\index{Swamp Crane}
\swamps{Swamp Crane}
\begin{marginfigure}
  \includegraphics{Swamp-Crane.jpg}
\end{marginfigure}

Swamp cranes are famous for defending their territory against all
intruders. They have long beaks and magical feathers which they can
shoot like darts for \SI{60}{ft}.\marginnote{Instead of providing the
  exact number of feathers they can shoot, simply assume that rolling
  a 1 on a damage roll means that this was the last feather and
  they'll attack with their beaks next round, coming into melee range.
  To read more about these birds, check our the Wikipedia entry on
  \href{https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stymphalian_birds}{Stymphalian
    birds}.} Loud noise from rattles, drums or bells scare them away.

\begin{quote}
HD~1 AC~13 1d4 F2 MV~18 ML~9 XP~100; shoot feathers like darts
\end{quote}

Not only are these cranes very aggressive, their dung is poisonous,
too. This is a big problem for settlements near an infested swamp.

\textbf{Numbers}: 3d12.

\notreasure

\textbf{Terrain}: swamps.



\section{Tengu}
\label{sec:tengu}
\index{Bird People|see {Tengu}}
\index{Crow People|see {Tengu}}
\index{Tengu}
\forests{Tengu}
\mountains{Tengu}
\begin{marginfigure}
  \includegraphics{Tengu.jpg}
\end{marginfigure}

There are two kind of tengu. If their human nature is strong, then
they are simply lightweight and have a very long nose. When their bird
nature is strong, they are smaller, covered in black feathers, with a
big crow beak in their face, and short wings that help them jump
around. They love to drink and get rowdy when they do. They almost
always are.

When sober, they can use the \textbf{duelling} stance: study a target
for two rounds and attack on the third round with a +4 bonus for
triple damage.

Whether drunk or sober, the bird people covet shiny things.

\begin{quote}
HD~2+1 AC~13 1d6 F2 MV~12 ML~9 XP~200; \emph{duelling} stance for up to
+4/3d6 in the third round
\end{quote}

\textbf{Numbers}: 1d12. When only one or two are encountered, these
are the bigger, more human looking tengu.

\textbf{Names}: Beak, Beaker, Beer, Bottle, Cherry, Drink, Fire, Wine.

\scout This is what remains of ancient treasures -- whatever was not
spent on the road.

\textbf{Terrain}: forests, mountains.



\section{Toad, Giant}
\label{sec:toad}
\index{Toad}
\caves{Toad}
\swamps{Toad}
\begin{marginfigure}
  \includegraphics{Toad.jpg}
\end{marginfigure}

Giant toads are lazy hunters. They don't like to move around a lot.
Instead, they wait for their prey to approach. These giant toads are
about as large as a cart and can easily swallow human children, elves,
halflings and dwarves. If an attack succeeds against such a target, it
is automatically \textbf{swallowed}. Any such victim is
\emph{drowning}: save vs.~death once per round or die. When swallowed
and not dead yet, you can use a dagger to try and cut yourself free.
No other weapon will do.

\begin{quote}
HD~4+1 AC~13 1d6 + \emph{swallow} F2 MV~3 ML~6 XP~400
\end{quote}

Giant toads are the favorite guard beasts of
\hyperref[sec:frogling]{froglings}.

\textbf{Numbers}: 1d6.

\notreasure

\textbf{Terrain}: caves, swamps.



\section{Treant}
\label{sec:treant}
\index{Treant}
\forests{Treant}
\jungles{Treant}
\swamps{Treant}
\begin{marginfigure}
  \includegraphics{Treant.jpg}
\end{marginfigure}

Treants are giant, sentient, ambulant trees. They are usually slow to
anger but axes and fire incite their ire. Every treant can
\textbf{animate} two ordinary trees within \SI{60}{ft} that fight just
like a treant. When at rest, treants are hard to distinguish from
trees and \textbf{surprise} their foes on 1–3 in 6.

The treant's roots can deal damage to built structures like walls or
palisades.

\begin{quote}
HD~8 AC~18 2d6/2d6 F8 MV~6 ML~6 XP~800; surprise; animate trees
\end{quote}

\textbf{Numbers}: 1d8.

\textbf{Names}: Oldfather, Birchwhip, Rootstrong, Mossman, Coldwater.

\poor Sometimes one finds the remains of an ancient elf lord or lady
in the treant's grove.

\textbf{Terrain}: forests, jungles, swamps.



\section{Troll}
\label{sec:troll}
\index{Troll}
\caves{Troll}
\forests{Troll}
\ruins{Troll}
\begin{marginfigure}
  \includegraphics{Troll.jpg}
\end{marginfigure}

Trolls look like living rock people, not as large as giants or ogres
but easily twice as broad, stocky, strong. When they hunker down, they
can easily be mistaken for a boulder. They will generate spontaneously
when rock is exposed to Earth Blood and hit by lightning. They prefer
to avoid the sunlight. A recent phenomenon has been trolls taking up
residence under bridges, asking for toll money in exchange for
maintaining them. Many of them also live in the cold, dark forests of
\hyperref[key:Niflheim]{Niflheim}.\marginnote{In a fight, trolls will
  not bite but instead \emph{headbutt} their target.}

When killed, the troll remains must be burned or dissolved in acid or
they'll slowly regenerate. A few minutes later, a troll rises
again, fully healed.

\begin{quote}
HD~6+1 AC~16 1d6/1d6/1d10 F6 MV~12 ML~10 XP~600; regeneration
\end{quote}

\textbf{Numbers}: 1d8.

\textbf{Names}: Stone, Rock, Boulder, Strong, Fist, Grey.

\textbf{Ingredients}: Alchemists have been trying to use troll blood
to regenerate lost limbs for years but without success. If you're
willing to risk it: some people have attached fresh troll limbs to the
stumps of their own lost arms or legs and managed to graft them onto
themselves. Most people fear that this will turn them into half-trolls
and servants of \hyperref[sec:hel]{Hel}, though.\marginnote{On a 1 in
  6, the limb will have a life of its own, taking up a retainer slot.}

\robber This is both collected tolls and ancient treasure kept.

\textbf{Terrain}: caves, forests, ruins.



\section{Unicorn}
\label{sec:unicorn}
\index{Unicorn}
\forests{Unicorn}
\begin{marginfigure}
  \includegraphics{Unicorn.jpg}
\end{marginfigure}

Unicorns are white magical horses with a long horn on their head. Once
per day, a unicorn can teleport up to \SI{360}{ft}, including a rider,
if any. A unicorn only bears a woman with a pure heart. Helping the
poor and downtrodden and all the animals is what a unicorn wants their
rider to do. Unicorns can communicate telepathically with their chosen
rider.

\begin{quote}
HD~4 AC~18 1d8/1d8/1d8 F8 MV~24 ML~7 XP~400; short teleport jump 1×/day
\end{quote}

\textbf{Numbers}: 1d8.

\textbf{Names}: Rainbow Kisses, Summer Breeze, Butterfly Heart, Love
Bubble, Happy Dance, Shining Diamond.

\textbf{Ingredients}: Unicorns horns and hair are often used in the
construction of powerful magic staffs and wands. A magic user or elf
of level 10 might be interested in buying them. The horn can be sold
for \SI{5000}{gp}, and there are d100 strands of hair long enough to
be sold, each worth \SI{50}{gp}.\averagevalue{7525}
% 5000 + 50.5*50

\notreasure

\textbf{Terrain}: forests.



\section{Valkyrie}
\label{sec:valkyrie}
\index{Valkyrie}
\air{Valkyrie}

Valkyries are the winged demons of battle. The can cross from realm to
realm on their \emph{flying horses}. When not on the field of battle,
collecting the souls of the dead, they are most often seen in
Sessrúmnir, Freya’s hall in Asgard, or in Valhalla, Odin’s hall in
Asgard.

\begin{quote}
  HD~6 AC~18 1d8 \emph{spear+3} F6 MV~18 ML~12 XP~600;
  \emph{planeshift}; flying; only harmed by magic or magic weapons
\end{quote}

When swinging the spear of a valkyrie, the wielder is
compelled\marginnote{When resisting such a compulsion for the third
  time, the spear loses its magic. The owner is considered unfit to
  wield it.} to shout for blood and glory as long and as loud as they
can. Also, when allies are fighting, the owner of such a spear is
compelled to draw it and join the melee.

\textbf{Numbers}: 1d6, each one on a \hyperref[sec:pegasus]{pegasus},
often in the company of a raven (if in the service of Odin) or a swan
(if in the service of Freya).

\textbf{Names}: War, Mercy, Spear, Cruel, Fight

\notreasure

\textbf{Terrain}: air.



\section{Vampire}
\label{sec:vampire}
\index{Vampire}
\ruins{Vampire}
\undead{Vampire}
\begin{marginfigure}
  \includegraphics{Vampire.jpg}
\end{marginfigure}

Vampires are dead humans, cursed with an eternal life fueled by the
blood of the living. This thirst consumes them and the longer they
fight this urge, the bloodier their feeding frenzy in the end.

When bitten by a vampire, victims are immediately \textbf{drained of
  two levels}.\marginnote{Victims reroll their remaining hit dice and
  keep this new hit point maximum if it is lower than their previous
  maximum. If their current hit points are higher than the new
  maximum, reduce them as well. Victims also lose their two best
  spells, if any, and reduce saving throws as appropriate.} Reduced to
zero levels, the victim will rise as a vampire spawn come midnight—an
eternal slave to their killer. No wonder are they mad with despair,
for no matter how much they long for company or lust for a human
touch, they are forever surrounded by scheming undead slaves. When
they are killed, all their slaves are freed and will disperse, looking
to start their own coven.

Vampire eyes are hypnotic: looking into them forces you to save
vs.~spells or be \textbf{charmed}.\marginnote{As time passes, more
  saving throws are granted to the victim:

  \medskip
  \begin{tabular}{cl}
    Intelligence & Timeframe \\
    3–8 & monthly \\
    9–12 & weekly \\
    13–18 & daily \\
  \end{tabular}
}

Vampires can \textbf{transform} into a bat or turn into a shapeless
mist at will. When reduced to zero hit points, a vampire will turn to
mist and flee back to its coffin. There, it will \textbf{regenerate}
over the next few hours. In order to kill it, a vampire must be found
in its coffin with no hit points, at which point it can be staked. The
wooden stake through its chest will prevent it from transforming
again. Note that the stake simply immobilises a vampire, it doesn't
die. To kill it, you must expose it to sunlight or submerge it under
running water for ten minutes.\marginnote{Vampires will avoid brightly
  illuminated areas and they will never step into running water.}

Vampires avoid facing \emph{mirrors} because they cast no reflection
and they will avoid attacking targets wearing a string of
\emph{garlic} around the neck. Vampires need to save vs.~poison in
order to attack such a target.

\begin{quote}
HD~9 AC~18 1d10 + \emph{drain} F9 MV~18 ML~11 XP~900; only harmed by
magic or magic weapons; unaffected by \emph{sleep}, \emph{charm}, and
other such mind affecting spells; charming gaze; transform into bat or
mist at will; regenerate
\end{quote}

It is said that at the end of time, all that will remain are lifeless
rocks floating through the emptiness of space, populated by vampires.

\textbf{Numbers}: 1d6. There will always be 2d6
\hyperref[sec:wolf]{wolves} in the vicinity.

\textbf{Names}: Igor the Hungry, Vlad the Impaler, Elisabeth the
Bloodthirsty, Dragana the Lonely, Acheron the Source of all Tears,
Karayan the Hunter, Lefu of the Dead.

\rich Their castles are sometimes full of riches from their former
lives.

\textbf{Terrain}: ruins.



\section{Vulture Demon}
\label{sec:vulturedemon}
\index{Vulture Demon}
\index{Demon|see {Vulture Demon}}
\air{Vulture Demon}

Vulture demons are the winged demons of pestilence sent out by
\hyperref[sec:pazuzu]{Pazuzu}. They bring misery and sickness wherever
they go.

\begin{quote}
  HD~8+1 AC~15 1d6/1d6/1d6/1d6/1d8 F16 MV~18 ML~11 XP~800;
  \emph{planeshift}; flying; only harmed by magic or magic weapons
\end{quote}

